- Root-cause localization reasoning: The rules state that when faults appear at different levels, pick the level with the most significant deviation from its threshold (>>50%). The container-level CPU throttling on shippingservice2-0 exhibits an orders-of-magnitude breach compared with its global thresholds, whereas node-6 I/O breaches are large but not as extreme by the same percentage rule. Trace error_rate series were mostly zero-valued (instrumentation/threshold artifacts) and logs/error_logs have no meaningful errors for further disambiguation.
- Conclusion from comparisons: The most plausible primary root cause is a container-level resource fault on shippingservice2-0 (container CPU throttling). Node-6 exhibits significant I/O pressure at the same time and could be a contributing factor (i.e., host I/O saturation leading to degraded container performance and scheduling/throttling), but the dominant, most severe abnormality by the breach metric is the container CPU throttling on shippingservice2-0.
- Remaining uncertainty: Whether the throttling is due to container-imposed cgroup limits (container-local misconfiguration) or an indirect effect of host resource pressure (node-6 I/O/memory causing scheduling or throttling behavior). Node CPU KPIs did not show host CPU saturation, but node disk I/O was heavily degraded at the same time, so host-level I/O contention is likely a contributing cause rather than the primary measured breach.

Given the diagnostic rules and the observed relative severities, we can localize the root cause to shippingservice2-0 with a precise first-occurrence timestamp. Traces and logs are inconclusive for further narrowing to a different component, and node-6 I/O issues are likely contributory but less severe by the breach metric.

